snippet.textDisplay: Adam Kownacki was not taken seriously before, so no one trained too hard to fight him. On the other hand, Adam started relaxing and did not take Helenius too seriously.  Photos and interviews during training instead of keeping his head in the game. LOL just like the Rocky movie.  I really had a feeling that this might happen, and it did.  Adam also has a very strong chin, but no chin is so strong that it can take any punch. He must work more on his defense and ducking punches.  Maybe Mike Tyson wobble?? :)  Adam will be back.  He's got a hart of a Polish Knight.

snippet.textDisplay: It's understandable that some people are in shock, but they don't remember what kind of punching power Helenius has. Helenius pounds of peak punching power is harder than Wilder's. Now, I'm not saying Helenius could take Wilder, even though Helenius is technically much better, Wilder is unpredictable, tall and has a very long reach. But in measure of how hard Robert can hit, he is there with the hardest of the hitters. He also has 200 amateur matches under his belt before going pro, so he has experience. But he has been known to let his guard down on backsteps and half moons, and those have cost him in important fights. In the Dillon Whyte fight Helenius showed that he is a good fighter and we have to remember he took that fight with an extremely short notice. Hope both fighters learned something from this fight, it was entertaining.
